Since you're on .NET 10, use the **built-in `TimeProvider`** — no custom wrapper needed.

## 1. Register in DI (`Program.cs`)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

## 2. Inject into `ReportGenerator`

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(TimeProvider timeProvider)
{
    public Report Generate()
    {
        var now = timeProvider.GetUtcNow();
        // use 'now' instead of DateTime.UtcNow
        ...
    }
}
```

## 3. Test with `FakeTimeProvider`

Install the test helper:

```
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing
```

Then in your test:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Time.Testing;

var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(
    new DateTimeOffset(2026, 5, 6, 12, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));

var generator = new ReportGenerator(fakeTime);
var report = generator.Generate();

Assert.Equal(new DateTime(2026, 5, 6, 12, 0, 0, DateTimeKind.Utc), report.GeneratedAt);

// You can also advance time:
fakeTime.Advance(TimeSpan.FromHours(1));
```

**Key points:**
- Replace every `DateTime.UtcNow` with `timeProvider.GetUtcNow()` (returns `DateTimeOffset`)
- `TimeProvider.System` is the real clock in production
- `FakeTimeProvider` gives you full control in tests — set fixed times, advance the clock, etc.

